as fascinated Jews and Gentiles, anti-Semites and philo-Semites alike. Much has been written about immigrant Jews in nineteenth- and twentieth-century New York City, but Gil Ribak’s critical look at the origins of Jewish liberalism in America provides a more complicated and nuanced picture of the Americanization process. Gentile New York examines these newcomers’ evolving feelings toward non-Jews through four critical decades in the American Jewish experience. Ribak considers how they perceived Gentiles in general as well as such different groups as “Yankees” (a common term for WASPs in many Yiddish sources), Germans, Irish, Italians, Poles, and African Americans. As they discovered the complexity of America’s racial relations, the immigrants found themselves at odds with “white” American values or behavior and were drawn instead into cooperative relationships with other minorities. Sparked with many previously unknown anecdotes, "ations, and events, Ribak’s research relies on an impressive number of memoirs, autobiographies, novels, newspapers, and journals culled from both sides of the Atlantic.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aGentilesxPublic opinion. 0aImmigrantszNew York (State)zNew YorkxAttitudes. 0aJewszNew York (State)zNew YorkxAttitudes. 0aJewszNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistoryy19th century. 0aJewszNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistoryy20th century. 0aPublic opinionzNew York (State)zNew York. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831106886100 cprintz978081355164740uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978081355219440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813552194423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780813552194/original  a978-3-11-068861-0  Rutgers University Pres